nd local particularity. Among the events treated in When Science and Christianity Meet are the Galileo affair, the seventeenth-century clockwork universe, Noah's ark and flood in the development of natural history, struggles over Darwinian evolution, debates about the origin of the human species, and the Scopes trial. Readers will be introduced to St. Augustine, Roger Bacon, Pope Urban VIII, Isaac Newton, Pierre-Simon de Laplace, Carl Linnaeus, Charles Darwin, T. H. Huxley, Sigmund Freud, and many other participants in the historical drama of science and Christianity. “Taken together, these papers provide a comprehensive survey of current thinking on key issues in the relationships between science and religion, pitched—as the editors intended—at just the right level to appeal to students.”—Peter J. Bowler, Isis  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChristianity. 0aReligion and sciencexHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  areligion, science, christianity, heresy, doctrine, scripture, sigmund freud, huxley, galileo, charles darwin, carl linnaeus, pierre-simon de laplace, isaac newton, pope urban viii, roger bacon, st augustine, scopes trial, evolution, origin of the species, natural history, flood, noahs ark, clockwork universe, medieval, cosmos, astronomy, matter, force, enlightenment, genesis, geology, nature, order, psychoanalysis, psychology, prayer-gauge debate, miracles, nonfiction.1 aAshworth, William B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroman, Thomas H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowne, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Mott T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarson, Edward J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aL